## Phase 1 — Read the Project

Use OpenCode’s file tools to read these before writing anything. You need this context to
generate code that fits seamlessly — wrong Lombok style, wrong naming convention, or wrong
Spring Boot version breaks integration.

```
pom.xml or build.gradle
  → java.version, spring-boot.version, is Lombok in dependencies?
  → spring-data-mongodb version (matters for annotation availability)

src/main/resources/application.yml (or .properties)
  → spring.data.mongodb.uri  → extract the database name from here
  → spring.data.mongodb.auto-index-creation  → flag if true in non-dev

src/main/java/**/config/Mongo*.java  (if exists)
  → Custom MongoTemplate? Custom converters? WriteConcern override?

src/main/java/**/*Document.java  or  *Entity.java  or  *Model.java
  → Naming convention (@Document classes) + Lombok annotations in use

src/main/java/**/*Repository.java
  → Method naming patterns + whether @Query is used + Pageable presence

src/main/java/**/*Service.java  (only files relevant to the task)
  → Join patterns + error handling style + how queries are called

src/main/java/**/*Controller.java  (only files relevant to the task)
  → Request params + DTO shapes + pagination contract
```

Capture this before Phase 2 — it drives every code decision:

```
java_version        → determines if records are available for DTOs
spring_boot_version → affects available annotations
uses_lombok         → @Data+@Builder vs plain getters/setters
naming_convention   → *Document | *Entity | plain POJO
db_name             → required for every MCP call
auto_index_creation → warn if true outside dev profile
existing_entities   → list of @Document classes already in project
```

