## Phase 3 — Generate Code

> Load `references/spring-data-mongodb-patterns.md` before writing any Java.

These rules are non-negotiable — each one prevents a specific category of bug:

```
@Document(collection = "exact_name_from_list_collections")   ← wrong name = empty results
@Field("db_name") when Java name ≠ MongoDB field name        ← missing = null fields
Never @DBRef — store ID as String, join in service            ← @DBRef causes N+1
Match Lombok + annotation style of the existing project       ← style inconsistency fails review
@Indexed on every field list_indexes showed                   ← missing = COLLSCAN
@CompoundIndex at class level for multi-field indexes
Pageable on all repo methods when count > 10K
MongoTemplate + Criteria for dynamic/multi-condition queries
Aggregation API (not raw JSON strings) for pipelines
Service layer owns all cross-collection joins
@CreatedDate + @LastModifiedDate if @EnableMongoAuditing present
```

Generate in this order (dependency order — each step uses the previous):

```
1. Enum classes          (referenced by entity — define first)
2. Embedded POJOs        (no @Document — used inside entity)
3. @Document entity      (the main class)
4. @Repository interface (query methods + Pageable)
5. Service methods       (business logic + joins + error handling)
6. DTO / Projection      (response shape — records on Java 17+)
7. MongoConfig changes   (only if new converters or index config needed)
```

